[normal]2.[bold]              [bold]General Overview[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]The transformation of Northern Ireland’s major 
[normal]retail
[normal] banks 
[normal]over
[normal] the last five years has been unprecedented in its speed and depth. In terms of ownership
[normal],
[normal] two banks are
[normal],
[normal] to all intents and purposes
[normal],
[normal] State-owned (although by different States); one bank enjoys minority State support with a significant North American shareholding; while the fourth remains in private ownership with its 
[normal]Danish
[normal] parent driving the most ambitious changes in its operating mod
[normal]el.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]None of the banks
[normal],
[normal] which have experienced 
[normal]major
[normal] changes in ownership
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]actively 
[normal]sought 
[normal]them: in each case State intervention w
[normal]as a last resort to prevent 
[normal]a worse
[normal] outcome. But in all cases 
[normal]key
[normal] decisions about the ownership or operation of these institutions – which have profound implications for the
[normal]ir
[normal] staff and customers 
[normal]in Northern Ireland 
[normal]– have been taken outside the jurisdiction – in 
[normal]either London
[normal], Edinburgh, Dublin or Copenhagen.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]              
[normal]Nort
[normal]hern Ireland may 
[normal]also suffer 
[normal]in terms of the quality of investment in its economic, commercial and social infrastructure. Northern Ireland may not 
[normal]rate
[normal] 
[normal]highly in
[normal] 
[normal]either strategic or operational priorities
[normal] 
[normal]– as Ulster Bank
[normal]’s customers
[normal] will readily testify 
[normal]when 
[normal]a
[normal] temporary
[normal] IT glitch for 
[normal]RBS and NatWest 
[normal]customers 
[normal]became
[normal] an IT meltdown for Ulster Bank – lasti
[normal]ng weeks.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] absence of any locally
[normal]-
[normal]owned banking institutions
[normal] may also have a negative impact on
[normal] the availability of credit within Northern Ireland
[normal] since it
[normal] turn
[normal]s
[normal] on lending policy decisions made elsewhere – by 
[normal]parent board
[normal]s 
[normal]with no
[normal] specific concern for the good 
[normal]of
[normal] Northern Ireland.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5
[normal]              
[normal]Danske[bold] Bank[bold] (formerly Northern Bank) is arguably the most financially sound of the major 
[normal]retail
[normal] banks operating in
[normal] Northern Ireland – since its more prudent
[normal] 
[normal]approach to lending meant that it 
[normal]largely avoided
[normal] the surge in speculative property lending 
[normal]which drove
[normal] Irish banking 
[normal]to the brink of 
[normal]collapse in 2008-9. 
[normal]Danske
[normal] Bank has recorded operating profits for a number of 
[normal]years and expects to return to overall profitability by the end of 
[normal]2013
[normal] – even after losses for impairments are 
[normal]included
[normal]. However, the position of 
[normal]Danske’s
[normal] Northern Ireland business contrast
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]with
[normal] its Republic of Ireland 
[normal]operation 
[normal](formerly National Irish Bank) – which became heavily involved in 
[normal]property 
[normal]lending 
[normal]before 
[normal]2008 and suffered 
[normal]accordingly
[normal]. The complete overhaul of 
[normal]Danske’s
[normal] Republic of Ireland business – with the virtual elimination of its branch network and its 
[normal]remodelling
[normal] as a niche business bank – has resulted in the transfer of some call centre traffic and processing work to units in Northern Ireland –
[normal] enhancing
[normal] the
[normal]ir viability.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal]              
[normal]The expansion in this activity has compensated in employment terms for the contraction i
[normal]n 
[normal]Danske’s
[normal] Branch network in Northern Ireland. Since 2005 the number of offices and sub-offices operated by the Bank has fallen from approximately 130
[normal] 
[normal]to fifty-two – with 
[normal]continuing
[normal] reduction
[normal]s
[normal] likely 
[normal]in
[normal] 2014. 
[normal]Unlike
[normal] other major banks wh
[normal]ere
[normal] branch closures
[normal] 
[normal]may have emerged as desperate cost-cutting measures
[normal], 
[normal]Danske
[normal]/Northern Bank has pursued a deliberate policy – over many years in terms of gestation and implementation – to make greater use of electronic channels to deliver services to customers. While all o
[normal]f the banks in Northern Ireland have begun to 
[normal]promote
[normal] e-banking for customers to some degree, 
[normal]Danske
[normal] Bank 
[normal]has gone furthest
[normal] 
[normal]both 
[normal]in terms of customer adoption of the technology and the reduction in the comparative density of its branch network.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]7
[normal]              
[normal]First[bold] Trust Bank[bold] is a wholly-owned subsidiary of AIB Group which in turn is 99% owned by the Irish State – as a result of the multi-billion euro public investment made to rescue the Group from the disastrous 
[normal]impact of its impaired loans
[normal]. As part of the restruct
[normal]uring of the Group’s overseas holdings required by the EU Commission, AIB’s 
[normal]Polish and US 
[normal]interests were sold. AIB also put its UK division – comprising First Trust Bank
[normal] (FTB)
[normal] and Allied Irish Bank (GB) – on the market. However, 
[normal]with no
[normal] significant interes
[normal]t from prospective buyers, the division was withdrawn from sale. Following substantial engagement by Northern Ireland Ministers and Assembly
[normal] 
[normal]members 
[normal]along with
[normal] concerted lobbying by members of IBOA, 
[normal]AIB
[normal] committed to 
[normal]remain
[normal] in Northern Ireland through 
[normal]FTB
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.8
[normal]              
[normal]AIB Group’s initial decision in 2012 to close over 
[normal]70 branches was primarily focus
[normal]ed on its Republic of Ireland business. 
[normal]Some
[normal] Northern Ireland 
[normal]locations 
[normal]were earmarked for closure under this 
[normal]programme
[normal] 
[normal]– b
[normal]ringing to 9 the total of offices and sub-offices which have closed since 2008. However, since 
[normal]FTB
[normal] continues to operate at a loss, management 
[normal]may 
[normal]seek further branch closures in No
[normal]rthern Ireland – requiring customers to make greater use of electronic banki
[normal]ng
[normal]. As AIB Group 
[normal]attempts to 
[normal]restructure its business to achiev
[normal]e
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] return to profitability 
[normal]and
[normal] to exit State ownership, FTB may also come under pressure from its parent to transfer 
[normal]some 
[normal]“back office” support operations to Dublin.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]9
[normal]              
[normal]After 
[normal]Danske
[normal] Bank, 
[normal]Ba[bold]nk of Ireland[bold] is probably
[normal] the soundest of the four major 
[normal]retail
[normal] banks in terms of its balance sheet performance. The Group 
[normal]received 
[normal]€4.7bn
[normal] in State
[normal] support. It 
[normal]is forecast to return to profit shortly
[normal] and is keen to reduc
[normal]e
