[normal] 
[normal]The Bank’s Northern Ireland 
[normal]operations 
[normal]have been restructured in the last three years from being a semi-autonomous entity to being a fully integrated part of an all-island business. Bank of Ireland also has 
[normal]a significant presence in Britain as the provider of banking services to the Post Office. It also maintains a niche presence in business banking in Britain. However, the viability of this operation 
[normal]may be in question following 
[normal]the EU Commission
[normal]’s decision
[normal] 
[normal]that the Bank should sell 
[normal]some 
[normal]parts of 
[normal]this
[normal] operation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.10
[normal]              
[normal]As for customer
[normal] acces
[normal]s, Bank of Ireland has committed to close the fewest locations of the four major banking groups. Since the onset of the crisis, it has closed nine offices and sub-offices in
[normal] Northern Ireland. However, although it 
[normal]may 
[normal]maintain a presence on most of its existing sites, the Bank's “new branch model” is built on customers accessing services through a battery of electronic devices (monitors, ATMs and dedicated phone lines linked t
[normal]o a call centre) rather than by face-to-face interaction with bank worker
[normal]s.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.11
[normal]              
[normal]Of the four 
[normal]major retail
[normal] banks operating in Northern Ireland, 
[normal]Ulster Bank[bold] has probably suffered most from the crisis, rela
[normal]ti
[normal]ve to its size. While Ulster Bank is a very 
[normal]significant player in Northern Ireland
[normal]’s banking sector
[normal], the majority of its business is located in the Republic of Ireland where it 
[normal]was
[normal] involved in 
[normal]pre-crash 
[normal]speculative property lending. Indeed Ulster Bank’s 
[normal]former
[normal] subsidiary, First Active (which has sin
[normal]ce been merged into the main business) was the first 
[normal]institutional lender
[normal] in the Republic to offer 100% mortgages.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.12
[normal]              
[normal]To
[normal] address the consequences of 
[normal]its
[normal] impaired loan book, Ulster Bank has relied on significant support from its parent, Royal Bank of Sco
[normal]tland – which
[normal] 
[normal]has been sustained on “life support” 
[normal]by
[normal] the State for almost five years. Ulster Bank has also embarked on two major cost-cutting initiatives – each involving 950 job losses achieved through voluntary severance. Although AIB has 
[normal]cut more jobs
[normal] 
[normal]in absolute terms, Ulster Bank has cut deepest 
[normal]relative
[normal] to the size of its workforce. Of the 1900 job cuts already implemented or announced for Ulster Bank, Northern Ireland has ac
[normal]c
[normal]ounted for around 700.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.13
[normal]              
[normal]Ulster Bank has also engaged in branch closure
[normal]s – primarily as a result of the merger of its First Active mortgage business. Having closed eleven offices and sub-offices in Northern Ireland since 2008,
[normal] 
[normal]the Bank is reviewing its branch network. However, s
[normal]enior executives recently told 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]’
[normal]s
[normal] outgoing 
[normal]Finance 
[normal]Minister
[normal], Sammy Wilson, that the number of b
[normal]ranches
[normal] 
[normal]in Northern Ireland to be closed in 2014 would not exceed nine.
