[normal]3.[bold]              [bold]The structure and governance of banks in Northern Ireland[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]As outlined at 2.2, none of the four major 
[normal]retail
[normal] banks in Northern Ireland are headquartered in the province. 
[normal]FTB
[normal] and Bank of Ireland are subsidiaries of Dublin
[normal]-
[normal]based banking groups. 
[normal]Danske’s
[normal] parent is based in Copenhagen, while Ulster Bank’s Dublin Head Office reports to RBS headquarters in Edinburgh. 
[normal]Of Northern Ireland
[normal]’s
[normal] second tier of financial institutions, only the Progressive Building Society could be 
[normal]regarded as
[normal] truly indigenous.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]The distance between the board rooms where key decisions about cr
[normal]edit and risk are made and the 
[normal]areas in Northern Ireland 
[normal]affected by them
[normal] 
[normal]is a further
[normal] concern – especially 
[normal]as many
[normal] banks with international interests 
[normal]have
[normal] 
[normal]retrenched
[normal] 
[normal]to
[normal] their home markets
[normal] since the crisis began
[normal]. 
[normal]Without the intervention of local public representatives, this trend may h
[normal]ave been more pronounced 
[normal]in Northern Ireland. 
[normal]T
[normal]h
[normal]ese
[normal] 
[normal]interventions
[normal] may have 
[normal]secured 
[normal]add
[normal]itional
[normal] traction because of the substantial level of State support for these institutions
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Northern Ireland’s
[normal] four largest 
[normal]retail banks
[normal] are
[normal] supervised to some degree
[normal] by three different regulatory bodies – none of which is 
[normal]located in
[normal] Northern Ireland. The recently established Financial Conduct Authority does not have a 
[normal]physical 
[normal]presence on the ground in Northern Ireland – nor did its predecessor, the Financial Services
[normal] Authori
[normal]ty. Quality of oversight is 
[normal]an important issue – in view of the recent history of irresponsible
[normal] 
[normal]behaviour
[normal] by
[normal] the 
[normal]leaderships
[normal] of key financial institutions in both Ireland and Britain – involving high risk property lending, 
[normal]mis
[normal]-selling of insurance-
[normal]based products and interest rate
[normal] manipulation – facilitated by 
[normal]light touch regulatory regimes in each jurisdiction. In such lax regulatory environments, 
[normal]banking leaders
[normal] were facilitated in 
[normal]adopting 
[normal]cavalier a
[normal]pproach
[normal]e
[normal]s – partly 
[normal]because they believed, correc
[normal]tly as it turned out, that if they got into major difficulties, the Stat
[normal]e would assist them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]              
[normal]Another key factor in the near collapse of 
[normal]banking has been 
[normal]the shift in the 
[normal]sector
[normal]’s prevailing
[normal] culture from one focused on customer service to one dictated 
[normal]by sales targets 
[normal]driven by
[normal] the 
[normal]pursuit of short-term profits
[normal]. 
[normal]The ongoing controversy around bonuses is one facet of culture. Equally troubling has been the pressure on bank workers to sell financial
[normal] ‘products’ – rather than to 
[normal]offer
[normal] dispassionate prudent financial advice to customers.
[normal] 
[normal]The
[normal] pressure 
[normal]on staff 
[normal]to meet targets
[normal] is now based on
[normal] the 
[normal]‘
[normal]stick
[normal]’
[normal] of disciplinary action rather than the 
[normal]‘
[normal]carrot
[normal]’
[normal] of performance awards. At the same time, 
[normal]bank workers
[normal] who speak out – even in the most 
[normal]general terms about the state of the 
[normal]sector
[normal] – 
[normal]risk
[normal] disciplinary action 
[normal]for
[normal] either breaching confidentiality or – with no hint of irony – damaging their employer’s reputation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]6
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] 
[normal]State’s 
[normal]pivotal
[normal] role 
[normal]in the financial sector 
[normal]at this time provides
[normal] a
[normal]n
[normal] op
[normal]portunity to embed a new culture – 
[normal]which would promote
[normal] the traditional values of prudential lending and 
[normal]genuine
[normal] customer service
[normal] – with technological advances
[normal] used to enhance such a development
[normal] rather
[normal] 
[normal]than being viewed primarily 
[normal]as a means of cutting costs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]7
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] composition of the boards of banks have been justifiably 
[normal]critici
[normal]s
[normal]ed
[normal] 
[normal]as
[normal] a circle of like-minded individuals (indeed with the same individuals frequently sharing interlocking memberships of a number of b
[normal]oard
[normal]s). Greater diversity of membership is e
[normal]ssential 
[normal]for
[normal] avoiding the high
[normal] level “group-think” which was 
[normal]apparent 
[normal]before the
[normal] banking crisis and, 
[normal]also
[normal], 
[normal]perhaps
[normal], 
[normal]since
[normal]. The inclusion of employee representatives with those of other stake-holders should be 
[normal]priorit
[normal]ised
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]8
[normal]              
[normal]At the 
[normal]sectoral
[normal] level, IBOA h
